  "prompt": "How can I tell an unknowing friend that I like him without making him feel awkward?",
  "response": "Telling a friend that you like them can be a delicate situation, but there are ways to approach it that can minimize awkwardness. Here are some tips:\n\n1. **Gauge Interest**: Pay attention to how he behaves around you. Look for signs that he might feel the same way, such as flirting, seeking out your company, or showing particular interest in your life.\n\n2. **Choose the Right Setting**: Find a comfortable, private setting where you can talk without distractions or interruptions. A relaxed environment can help ease any tension.\n\n3. **Be Honest but Casual**: You might say something like, \u201cI really value our friendship, and I need to share something with you. I\u2019ve developed feelings for you. I hope this doesn\u2019t change anything between us.\u201d This keeps the tone light and lets him know your intention is not to pressure him.\n\n4. **Focus on Your Feelings**: Frame it around your feelings rather than making it a declaration about him. This way, he won\u2019t feel like he has to respond immediately or choose between something or nothing. \n\n5. **Be Ready for Any Response**: Understand that he might not feel the same way, and that\u2019s okay. Let him know it\u2019s fine if he doesn\u2019t reciprocate your feelings and that you value the friendship regardless.\n\n6. **Keep It Light**: If the sentiment is shared, you can approach the potential changes in your relationship gradually. If it\u2019s not, you can show him that you\u2019re still a good friend and that nothing has to change drastically.\n\n7. **Follow Up**: After expressing your feelings, give him some space to process. You can follow up later to check in on how he\u2019s feeling about the conversation.\n\nUltimately, clear communication and honesty are key, and being considerate of his feelings will help maintain the friendship regardless of the outcome.",
